{"title_page": "Norbert Balatsch", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian conductor and chorus master|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Norbert Balatsch\n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1928|03|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Vienna\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|05|06|1928|03|10|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Wiener S\u00e4ngerknaben]]\n| occupation          = {{plainlist|\n* Chorale conductor\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| organization        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Vienna State Opera]]\n* [[Bayreuth Festival]]\n* [[Orchestra dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia|Coro dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia]]\n}}\n| awards              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Grammy Award]]s\n* [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Norbert Balatsch''' (10 March 1928 \u2013 6 May 2020) was an Austrian conductor, espeacially choral conductor, a [[baritone]] singer, and an academic teacher. He the long-term choral conductor of both the [[Vienna State Opera]] and the [[Bayreuth Festival]]. Two of his recordings won [[Grammy Awards]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in [[Vienna]],<ref name=\"ORF\" /> He was a member of the ''[[Wiener S\u00e4ngerknaben]]'' boys' choir from 1938 to 1944.<ref name=\"Bayreuth\" /> From 1952, Balatsch was a [[baritone]] in the opera chorus of the [[Vienna State Opera]]. A year later, he also became choral conductor of a Vienna men's chorus, the Wiener M\u00e4nnergesang-Verein.<ref name=\"WZ\" /> At the State Opera, he eventually became the long-term choral conductor at the house, first leading the Extrachor from 1965, then as vice choral conductor in 1967, and in 1968 as ''Chordirektor'' (chorus director), a position he held to 1983.<ref name=\"ORF\" /><ref name=\"Vienna\" />\n\nIn the early 1970s, he was directed the [[Philharmonia Chorus|New Philharmonia Chorus]], which was previously and later known as the Philharmonia Chorus.<ref name=\"Philharmonia\" /> He was the chorus director of the [[Bayreuth Festival]] from 1972 to 1999, collaborating with conductors such as [[Daniel Barenboim]], [[Karl B\u00f6hm]], [[Dennis Russell Davies]], [[Colin Davis]], [[Heinrich Hollreiser]], [[Eugen Jochum]], [[Carlos Kleiber]], [[James Levine]], [[Peter Schneider (conductor)|Peter Schneider]], [[Giuseppe Sinopoli]], [[Georg Solti]], [[Horst Stein]] and [[Silvio Varviso]].<ref name=\"Bayreuth\" /> From 1976, he prepared the choir for the ''[[Jahrhundertring]]'' there, staged by [[Patrice Ch\u00e9reau]] and conducted by [[Pierre Boulez]].<ref name=\"Bilsing\" /> The performances were broadcast live and recorded. From 1983, Balatsch was the choral conductor of the [[Orchestra dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia|Coro dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia]]. In concerts with [[Lorin Maazel]], he prepared the chorus for Beethoven's [[Ninth Symphony]] and ''[[Fidelio]]'', and ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' by Berlioz.<ref name=\"Maazel\" /> From 1999 to 2001, Balatsch was director of the Wiener S\u00e4ngerknaben.<ref name=\"WZ\" />\n\nBalatsch prepared choruses for numerous recordings, two of which won [[Grammy Award]]s in the category Best Choral Performance, Mozart's [[Requiem (Mozart)|Requiem]] in 1980, and and Bach's ''[[St Matthew Passion]]'' in 2001.<ref name=\"Grammy\" /> In 2006, he returned to the Vienna State Opera for a production of Schoenberg's ''[[Moses und Aron]]''. He was awarded honorary membership of the house after the last performance of that production on 19 June 2006.<ref name=\"ORF\" />\n\nBalatsch died on 6 May 2020 at age 92.<ref name=\"Bayreuth\" />\n\n== Awards ==\nBalatsch was awarded the Goldener Ehrenring (Ring of honour in gold) from [[Bayreuth]].<ref name=\"Bayreuth Ehrenring\" /> He received the Ehrenring from the Vienna State Opera.<ref name=\"Vienna Ehrenring\" /> In 2008, he was awarded the great cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (Cavaliere di Gran Croce Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana).<ref name=\"Quirinale\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Bayreuth\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.bayreuther-festspiele.de/en/festspiele/news/2020/death-of-long-time-former-choir-director-prof-norbert-balatsch/\n| title = Death of long-time former choir director Prof. Norbert Balatsch\n| website = [[Bayreuth Festival]]\n| date = 8 May 2020\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bayreuth Ehrenring\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.bayreuth.de/rathaus-buergerservice/stadtverwaltung/ehrungen-auszeichnungen/goldener-ehrenring/\n| title = Goldener Ehrenring\n| website = [[Bayreuth]]\n| date = 8 May 2020\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/norbert-balatsch\n| title = Artist / Norbert Balatsch\n| website = [[Grammy Awards]]\n| date = 2020\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Maazel\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.santacecilia.it/file_gallery/MAESTRO_LORIN_MAAZEL_-_SANTA_CECILIA.pdf\n| title = Maestro Lorin Maazel / Orchestra e Coro dell\u2019Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia\n| website = santacecilia.it\n| date = \n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ORF\">{{cite web\n| url = https://orf.at/stories/3164802/\n| title = Ehemaliger Staatsopernchordirektor Balatsch ist tot\n| website = [[ORF]]\n| date = 7 May 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Philharmonia\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.guildmusic.com/shop/wbc.php?tpl=artistdruck.html&pid=13842\n| title = Biography of The Philharmonia Chorus\n| website = guildmusic.com\n| date = 2020\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Quirinale\">{{cite web\n| url = https://archivio.quirinale.it/aspr/comunicati/PRESSRELEASE-001-009787/presidente/giorgio-napolitano/il-presidente-napolitano-ha-ricevuto-maestro-norbert-balatsch#n\n| title = Comunicato\n| website = archivio.quirinale.it\n| date = 2009\n| language = it\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bilsing\">{{cite web\n| last = Bilsing\n| first = Peter\n| url = http://www.omm.de/cds/dvds/oper/DG-boulez-ring.html\n| title = Richard Wagner / Der Ring des Nibelunen / Oft kopiert \u2013 nie erreicht\n| website = Online Musik Magazin\n| date = 2009\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vienna\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.wiener-staatsoper.at/die-staatsoper/aktuelles/detail/news/zum-tod-von-prof-norbert-balatsch/\n| title = Zum Tod von Prof. Norbert Balatsch\n| newspaper = [[Vienna State Opera]]\n| date = 7 May 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vienna Ehrenring\">{{cite web\n| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140226033623/http://www.juwelier-wagner.at/die-welt-von-wagner/kultur/ehrenring-der-wiener-staatsoper/\n| title = Ehrenring der Wiener Staatsoper\n| website = juwelier-wagner.at\n| language = de\n| date = \n<!--\n| archiveurl = http://www.juwelier-wagner.at/die-welt-von-wagner/kultur/ehrenring-der-wiener-staatsoper/\n| archivedate = 4 May 2019-->\n| accessdate = 25 August 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WZ\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/kultur/klassik/2059887-Der-Erzengel-der-Chorleiter.html\n| title = Der Erzengel der Chorleiter / Zum Tod von Norbert Balatsch - der international renommierte Wiener Chorleiter ist im Alter von 92 Jahren gestorben.\n| newspaper = [[Wiener Zeitung]]\n| date = 8 May 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 8 May 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|122327462}}\n* [https://www.musiklexikon.ac.at/ml/musik_B/Balatsch_Norbert.xml Balatsch, Norbert] OEML\n* {{IMDb name|1363017}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balatsch, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian conductor and chorus master|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Norbert Balatsch\n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1928|03|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Vienna\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|05|06|1928|03|10|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Wiener S\u00e4ngerknaben]]\n| occupation          = {{plainlist|\n* Chorale conductor\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| organization        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Vienna State Opera]]\n* [[Bayreuth Festival]]\n* [[Orchestra dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia|Coro dell'Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia]]\n}}\n| awards              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Grammy Award]]s\n* [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Norbert Balatsch''' (10 March 1928 \u2013 6 May 2020) was an Austrian conductor, espeacially choral conductor, a [[baritone]] singer, and an academic teacher. He the long-term choral conductor of both the [[Vienna State Opera]] and the [[Bayreuth Festival]]. Two of his recordings won [[Grammy Awards]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in [[Vienna]],<ref name=\"ORF\" /> He was a member of the ''[[Wiener S\u00e4ngerknaben]]'' boys' choir from 1938 to 1944.<ref name=\"Bayreuth\" /> From 1952, Balatsch was a [[baritone]] in the opera chorus of the [[Vienna State Opera]]. A year later, he also became choral conductor of a Vienna men's chorus, the Wiener M\u00e4nnergesang-Verein.<ref name=\"WZ\" /> At the State Opera, he eventually became the long-term choral conductor at the house, first leading the Extrachor from 1965, then as vice choral conductor in 1967, and in 1968 as ''Chordirektor'' (chorus director), a position he held to 1983.<ref name=\"ORF\" /><ref name=\"Vienna\" />\n\nIn the early 1970s, he was directed the [[Philharmonia Chorus|New Philharmonia Chorus]], which was